Rating: 4
This soup is a nice starter for Thanksgiving and/or a festive fall meal. I am not a fan of allspice in large quantities, so 1/8-1/4 tsp is sufficient. 1/2 tsp cayenne pepper gives just the right amount of "zip" or heat to this bisque. I did use one additional clove of garlic (never can have too much garlic). I added one 13.5 oz can of lite coconut milk and using the full can did not thin the bisque too much, nor detract from the flavor. The decrease in the amount of fat and calories here is a savings about 50% for the calorie conscious. I used about 1 Tbsp of sugar to balance out the heat and bring out the flavor of the coconut a bit more. A small amount of ginger really completes this. I did not have fresh today (which I would recommend) so I used about 1/4 tsp of ground. I utilized an immersion blender which made clean up a snap. I think that there are a lot of different types of toppings that can be used here: Toasted pumpkin seeds, freshly grated coconut or just a swirl of coconut milk through the middle of the bisque. I love soup in general and am always looking for interesting flavors for the various seasons. Enjoy!

Rating: 4
Took the advise of a few of the reviews and added some kick. My soup turned out so flavorful!! Here are my adjustments: *add 1 more garlic glove *1 tsp minced ginger *only blend 2/3 of the soup for 4 seconds, keeping the other 1/3 with the pumpkin cubes and soup broth *add 1/2 tsp cheyenne pepper, 1/2 tsp crushed pepper, dash chili powder (i did not have allspice) *only used 1/4 cup thick coconut milk, anymore would be too sweet

