Rating: 2
I was excited to try this soup since the recipe is easy and it can be made quickly with ingredients I already had in the pantry. However, I was extremely dissapointed in the original recipe; it was bland and the canned pumpkin tasted like tin (I used Libby brand). Yuck. I doctored it up using some recommendations from previous posts. I used 2 onions instead of 1, I added 5 (FIVE!) teaspoons of sugar, 1.5 tsps. of allspice, 1 tsp of cinnamon, a dash of ginger, 2 tablespoons of peanut butter, and a dash of cayenne. (Basically I added all the ingredients for a spicy pumpkin bread recipe) It is still pretty bland and quite disspointing. The recipe seemed promising, but I definitely would't make it the same way again. I suspect it is the canned pumpkin that really kills it. Next time I will roast a pie pumpkin, although that sort of defeats the purpose of a quick and easy midweek recipe.

Rating: 3
I used fresh cooking pumpkin, split it in 4 pieces, roasted on a baking sheet faced down until cooked through. This gives you rich, concentrated flavor, not watery bland flavor of canned. I used a lot less coconut - it's nice but too much makes it too sweet and coconutty. Used additional water to thin instead. I also used fresh grated ginger. These changes made the soup taste a lot better.

